 (then Medical Department of Williams College)","dates":"1829-12-16","type":"medical","notes":"Graduated Berkshire Medical College December 16, 1829."},{"school_name":"Post-graduate medical study, New York and Philadelphia","type":"post-graduate","notes":"Studied medicine in New York and Philadelphia after graduation."}],"career":[{"role":"Physician (general practice)","organization":"Private practice, Meadville PA","location":"Meadville, Crawford County, Pennsylvania","start_year":1826,"end_year":1885,"notes":"Came to Meadville 1826 (then a comparatively new and unsettled region) due to delicate health requiring a change of climate. For many years had to ride on horseback to all parts of Crawford County, largely through forests where 'blazed' trees (marked by the axe) were the only guides. Practiced for nearly 60 years until his death. The oldest practicing physician in Meadville at his death."},{"role":"First President","organization":"Crawford County Medical Society","location":"Meadville, Pennsylvania","start_year":1832,"notes":"Organized the Crawford County Medical Society at Meadville PA in 1832 and served as its first President for many years."},{"role":"Warden then Vestryman","organization":"Christ Church, Meadville (Episcopal)","location":"Meadville, Crawford County, Pennsylvania","end_year":1885,"notes":"Warden for many years; later Vestryman at Christ Church Meadville — where son-in-law Rev. Marison Byllesby served as Rector."},{"role":"Manufacturing investor (unsuccessful)","organization":"Various Meadville enterprises","location":"Meadville, Pennsylvania","notes":"Largely interested in manufacturing and other enterprises which promised to contribute to Meadville's prosperity but proved unfortunate investments — resulted in total loss of his large property. His losses 'neither lessened the cheerfulness of his temper nor his kindness of heart' per History of Crawford County 1885."}],"military_service":[],"institutions":[{"institution_id":"INST043","relationship":"alumnus"}],"landmarks":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"artworks":[],"tags":["physician","massachusetts_migration","pennsylvania_migration"],"research_tags":[],"cross_connections":[],"narrative_blocks":[{"number":1,"category":"career","header":"Sixty-year Meadville physician, oldest at death","body":"Dr. Edward Ellis came west to Meadville Pennsylvania in 1826 at age twenty-two — then a comparatively new and unsettled region — because of delicate health requiring a change of climate. For many years he rode on horseback to all parts of Crawford County, often through forests where blazed trees marked by the axe were his only guides. He practiced medicine there for nearly sixty years and was the oldest practicing physician in Meadville at his death in 1885."},{"number":2,"category":"family","header":"Two wives died early, one daughter survived","body":"Edward Ellis was twice widowed — his first wife Mary M. Kennedy died in 1840 after eight years of marriage, and his second wife Sarah Buchanan died in 1844 after only two years. From his second marriage came one daughter Elizabeth Ruth, who in 1864 married Rev. Marison Byllesby — then Rector of Christ Church Meadville, the same parish where Edward Ellis served as Warden and Vestryman."}],"quotes":[],"sources":[{"label":"FindAGrave #71489011","url":"https://www.findagrave.com/memorial/71489011/edward-ellis"},{"label":"History of Crawford County Pennsylvania, Warner Beers & Co., 1885, page 736"}],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"slug":"edward-ellis-1804"},"neighborhood":{"focus":{"id":"HD4235","slug":"edward-ellis-1804","n":"Doctor Edward Ellis M.D.","by":1804,"dy":1885,"sx":"u","hd":true,"td":false,"ee":false,"g":7},"spouses":[{"order":1,"spouse":{"id":"I00653","slug":"mary-kennedy-1807","n":"Mary M. Kennedy Ellis","by":1807,"dy":1840,"sx":"u","hd":false,"td":false,"ee":false,"g":null},"year":1832,"children":[]},{"order":2,"spouse":{"id":"I00654","slug":"sarah-buchanan-1807","n":"Sarah Buchanan Ellis","by":1807,"